Pareto Analysis of Fashion Product Defects in Excel
Project Overview:
This project analyzes common defects found in fashion products using the Pareto Principle (80/20 Rule) and Microsoft Excel. The goal is to identify the most frequent defects and determine which issues should be prioritized for quality improvement.

Dataset:
The dataset contains defect categories and their frequencies:
Defect Category	Frequency
Easy to Tear	10
Loose Stitching	7
Color Fading	5
Easily Stretched	3
Peeling Print	1

Objectives:
Identify the most common defects in fashion products.
Apply Pareto Analysis to determine priority issues.
Visualize defect frequencies and cumulative percentages.
Support quality control decision-making.

Tools Used:
Microsoft Excel
Pareto Chart
Data Visualization Techniques

Analysis Process:
Collect defect frequency data.
Sort defects from highest to lowest frequency.
Calculate cumulative frequency.
Calculate cumulative percentage.
Create a Pareto Chart in Excel.
Interpret results based on the 80/20 principle.

Key Findings:
Easy to Tear is the most common defect.
Loose Stitching and Color Fading are the next major issues.
The top three defect categories contribute to the majority of quality problems.
Focusing improvement efforts on these defects can significantly enhance product quality.

Visualization
The project includes a Pareto Chart showing:
Defect frequency (bars)
Cumulative percentage (line)
This visualization helps identify critical defects that should receive immediate attention.

Business Insights
By addressing the most frequent defects first, fashion manufacturers can:
Reduce product returns
Improve customer satisfaction
Increase product durability
Optimize quality control resources

